<DocsLayout title="Legal Search" description="Search jurisprudence with graph-led retrieval and explainable results.">
  <h1>Legal Search</h1>
  <span class="badge badge-dev">in development</span>

  <p>
    Jurisprudence search in the ecosystem goes through Valter. The current flow
    prioritizes <strong>graph-led retrieval</strong>, using the legal graph as the
    main discovery path while lexical and semantic search remain as complement and fallback.
  </p>

  <h2>How it works</h2>

  <ol>
    <li>The question enters Valter through REST API or MCP</li>
    <li>The Neo4j graph tries to discover relevant legal paths first</li>
    <li>Lexical and semantic search run in parallel to improve coverage</li>
    <li>Results are calibrated, verified, and explained</li>
    <li>Leci and Douto can join as additional grounding when needed</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Example</h2>

  <h4>Request</h4>

<pre><code>POST /api/v1/retrieve/search
Content-Type: application/json

{"{"}
  "query": "product liability for defective goods",
  "top_k": 5,
  "filters": {"{"}
    "minister": "Nancy Andrighi"
  {"}"}
{"}"}</code></pre>

  <h4>Response</h4>

<pre><code>{"{"}
  "matches": [
    {"{"}
      "document_id": "REsp_1234567_SP",
      "title": "REsp 1.234.567/SP",
      "why_it_matches": [
        "shared legal criterion",
        "relevant statutory provision",
        "connected precedent path"
      ]
    {"}"}
  ],
  "reasoning_chain": {"{"}
    "primary_path": "graph",
    "fallback_used": false
  {"}"},
  "grounding_sources": ["jurisprudence"]
{"}"}</code></pre>

  <h2>What makes it different</h2>

  <p>
    Instead of treating the graph as a secondary signal, Valter uses legal structure
    as the main retrieval axis. That improves explainability, enables traceable
    reasoning chains, and reduces dependence on opaque ranking heuristics.
  </p>

  <h2>Available via</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><a href="/api/rest">Valter REST API gateway</a></li>
    <li><a href="/api/mcp">Valter MCP gateway</a></li>
  </ul>
